english:
  title: Examination Question on Heaven, Earth, and the Ten Thousand Things
  author: Kim Sim
  language: eng
  text: 'I pose this question: Heaven, earth, and the ten thousand things do not escape three principles: Principle (理), Material Force (氣), and Number (數). When we speak of the Infinite (無極) and the Supreme Ultimate (太極), do we refer exclusively to Principle? Or can Material Force and Number also be discussed? Which comes first between Principle and Material Force, and which comes after? The ancients said, "Principle was investigated through Ichuan; Number was developed through Kangzhai." Did the earlier Confucian scholars each harbor particular biases, or did some achieve a comprehensive view that omitted nothing? The ancient sages spoke much of Principle—but did they also speak of Material Force and Number? Consider works such as the Yilin of the Jiaos, the Trigram Phases of Jingfang, the Taixuan of Yangxiong, and the Jingshi of Shao Yong—do these truly accord with the intent of the Changes as transmitted from the ancients? Shao Yong said, "Even the Material Force and Number of heaven and earth have an end where they become exhausted." Is it not strange to view heaven and earth so diminutively? When Material Force and Number reach their limit, does Principle also disappear with them? The doctrine of Epoch, Era, Period, and Year—what is its foundation? How can it be verified? If the rise and fall of nations and states, the success and failure of every matter and thing, all depend upon Material Force and Number, then can the theories of numerologists and small accounts also claim legitimate ancestry and warrant belief? Taking Mencius''s saying that "order alternates with chaos," can we truly extend this principle clearly through the Song and Yuan dynasties? If we cling solely to Material Force and Number, we fall into apocryphal and mysterious texts while human affairs are neglected; if we abandon Material Force and Number, we lose ourselves in mere activity while the Way of Heaven vanishes. How shall we reconcile these two extremes? Let all students attempt a thorough discourse upon this.'
  footnotes:
    - Ichuan (伊川) refers to Cheng Yi, and Kangzhai (康節) refers to Shao Yong, major Neo-Confucian philosophers who emphasized Principle and Number respectively.
    - The referenced classical works—Yilin, Trigram Phases, Taixuan, and Jingshi—are texts that attempt to decode patterns of change and cycles in the cosmos.
    - The doctrine of Epoch, Era, Period, and Year (元會運世) refers to a cyclical theory of cosmic time.
    - Apocryphal texts (讖緯) refer to prophecies and esoteric interpretations often considered unreliable.
